## Filter the data to include only records from 1850-01-01 to 2015-12-01
new_dataset <- df %>%
  filter(dt >= as.Date("1850-01-01") & dt <= as.Date("2015-12-01")) %>%
  mutate(dt = ymd(dt))

## We will create separate dataframes for each of the three temperature variables we want to plot

land_temp <- new_dataset[, c("dt", "LandAverageTemperature")]
land_ocean_temp <- new_dataset[, c("dt", "LandAndOceanAverageTemperature")]
land_max_temp <- new_dataset[, c("dt", "LandMaxTemperature")]
## We will convert the date column to a date format using the as.Date() function:

land_temp$dt <- as.Date(land_temp$dt)
land_ocean_temp$dt <- as.Date(land_ocean_temp$dt)
land_max_temp$dt <- as.Date(land_max_temp$dt)
## We will set the date column as the index for each of the dataframes using the xts package:
library(xts)
## 
## Attaching package: 'xts'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     first, last
land_temp_xts <- xts(land_temp$LandAverageTemperature, order.by = land_temp$dt)
land_ocean_temp_xts <- xts(land_ocean_temp$LandAndOceanAverageTemperature, order.by = land_ocean_temp$dt)
land_max_temp_xts <- xts(land_max_temp$LandMaxTemperature, order.by = land_max_temp$dt)
## Now, we can create line plots for each of the temperature variables using the plot() function

plot(land_temp_xts, main = "Land Average Temperature", ylab = "Temperature (°C)")

plot(land_ocean_temp_xts, main = "Land and Ocean Average Temperature", ylab = "Temperature (°C)")

plot(land_max_temp_xts, main = "Land Maximum Temperature", ylab = "Temperature (°C)")

## We can also create smoother plots using the ggplot2 package. First, we need to convert the xts objects to data frames

land_temp_df <- data.frame(Date = index(land_temp_xts), LandAverageTemperature = coredata(land_temp_xts))
land_ocean_temp_df <- data.frame(Date = index(land_ocean_temp_xts), LandAndOceanAverageTemperature = coredata(land_ocean_temp_xts))
land_max_temp_df <- data.frame(Date = index(land_max_temp_xts), LandMaxTemperature = coredata(land_max_temp_xts))
## Next, we will use the ggplot() function to create smoother plots

ggplot(land_temp_df, aes(x = Date, y = LandAverageTemperature)) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  labs(title = "Land Average Temperature", y = "Temperature (°C)") 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

## LandAndOceanAverageTemperature vs Time

ggplot(land_ocean_temp_df, aes(x = Date, y = LandAndOceanAverageTemperature)) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  labs(title = "Land and Ocean Average Temperature", y = "Temperature (°C)")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

## LandMaxTemperature vs Time

ggplot(land_max_temp_df, aes(x = Date, y = LandMaxTemperature)) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  labs(title = "Land Maximum Temperature", y = "Temperature (°C)")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

## We can use the rollmean() function from the zoo package
library(zoo)
## Convert date column to a date format

new_dataset$dt <- as.Date(new_dataset$dt)
## Create an xts object

new_dataset_xts <- xts(new_dataset$LandAndOceanAverageTemperature, order.by = new_dataset$dt)
## Calculate 10-year moving average / rolling average / running average

new_dataset_ma <- rollmean(new_dataset_xts, k = 120, align = "right", fill = NA)
## Plot the data and the moving average / rolling average / running average

plot(new_dataset_xts, main = "Land and Ocean Average Temperature", ylab = "Temperature (°C)", col = "blue")

lines(new_dataset_ma, col = "red", lwd = 2)

## In the code above, we first convert the date column to a date format and create an xts object. 
## We then use the rollapply() function to calculate a 10-year rolling average with a window size of 120 (10 years * 12 months), using the mean function to calculate the average value for each window. 
## We align the rolling average to the right of the data and fill any missing values with NA. 
## Finally, we plot the original data and the rolling average using the plot() function and add the rolling average as a line using the lines() function.

## The resulting plot shows the Land and Ocean Average Temperature data in blue and the 10-year rolling average in red. 
## We can observe that the 10-year rolling average follows a similar upward trend as the original data, but with a smoother curve. 
## The rolling average captures the long-term trend in the data while preserving some of the short-term variability. 
## We can also see that the temperature increase is more pronounced in recent decades, and the trend appears to be accelerating. 
## This graph demonstrates the usefulness of the rolling average in identifying long-term trends while preserving some of the short-term variability in time series data.
